(223, 1, '2017-07-16 11:22:48', '2017-07-16 10:22:48', 'When you have a huge website with many sub-sub pages and there is that one important for you page that you visit quite often but to get there you need to pass by another 999 other pages, you can easily make a link on your admin bar a have a quick access which gives you the opportunity to visit is by only one click.\r\n\r\nQuick link on your admin bar\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-221" src="http://localhost:8888/ivelin.me//wp-content/uploads/2017/07/toolbar-btn-example.png" alt="" width="751" height="33" />\r\n\r\nAdd this code to your functions.php\r\n<pre class="lang:js decode:true ">if (!function_exists(\'add_toolbar_link\')) {\r\n function add_toolbar_link($wp_admin_bar) {\r\n  $args1 = array(\r\n   \'id\' =&gt; \'ss_store\',\r\n   \'title\' =&gt; __(\'Example Link 1\', \'blank_theme\'),\r\n   \'href\' =&gt; home_url(\'/\'),\r\n   \'meta\' =&gt; array(\'class\' =&gt; \'ss-toolbar-custom\', \'title\' =&gt; __(\'Example Link 1\', \'blank_theme\'))\r\n  );\r\n  $wp_admin_bar-&gt;add_node($args1);\r\n }\r\n add_action(\'admin_bar_menu\', \'add_toolbar_link\', 999);\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\nQuick explanation\r\n\r\nSo we create an object called $args1 and we pass it some arguments like id, title, href and meta. To customise it change the "Example Link 1" to whatever you like and the href with the link to your page. Using $wp_admin_bar lets us attach that object to the already created by wordpress global variable. The last line of code hooks and calls the function add_toolbar_link by using the hook add_action to the admin_bar_menu.', 'Quick link to a page on your Wordpress admin bar', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '219-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-07-16 11:22:48', '2017-07-16 10:22:48', '', 219, 'http://localhost:8888/ivelin.me//219-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(224, 1, '2016-07-29 09:24:02', '2016-07-29 08:24:02', 'I will give you an example of how I have used it. I was given an image of a house plan and also pictures taken from the actual house. So, the requirement from the client was, when a user hovers over different areas (like the living room for example), the picture of the living room to appear next to the cursor. The example code below is given with a div and an image to differentiate the elements. I am not going to concentrate on the HTML, I will only give an example of how it looks and will explain the functionality after the JS code.\r\n<h3>Simple HTML example (dont forget to style it)</h3>\r\n<div class="code">\r\n<pre class="lang:default decode:true ">&lt;div&gt;\r\n&lt;img src="your image location" /&gt;\r\n&lt;/div&gt;</pre>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>The JS functionality</h3>\r\n<div class="code">\r\n<pre class="lang:js decode:true ">var $img = $(\'img\');\r\n$img.hide();\r\n$(\'div\').mousemove(function(e) {\r\n $img.stop(1, 1).fadeIn();\r\n $(\'img\').offset({\r\n  top: e.pageY - $img.outerHeight(),\r\n  left: e.pageX - ($img.outerWidth()/2)\r\n });\r\n}).mouseleave(function() {\r\n $img.fadeOut();\r\n});</pre>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nSo A quick explanation. It declares the image as a variable $img and hides it. Then it checks if the user has hovered over the div with the functions mousemove and mouseleave. If it has hovered, then it stops any kind of animation and fades the image on screen. Then it finds the parameters of the cursor on the screen and sets the image on top center of it. If you have many images and many \'hover spots\' on a image, you can use a image mapping and according to the different ID\'s to fade in different images. Voila!', 'Hover image and show it next to the cursor', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'hover-image-and-show-it-next-to-the-cursor', '', '', '2017-07-16 18:26:26', '2017-07-16 17:26:26', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/ivelin.me//?p=224', 0, 'post', '', 0),
